(3381, 3, '2016-07-22 12:39:41', '2016-07-22 12:39:41', '[tg_header title=\"Explore the Untouched Nepal\" subtitle=\"Rafting, Kayaking, and Trekking\"]\r\n\r\nThe Tamur River adventure combines one of the world’s finest rivers with a world-famous Himalayan trek.\r\n\r\nHands down the best multi-sport trip in Nepal, the Tamur River adventure starts with four days of trekking and camping through woodland and meadows, following a ridgeline at around 3000m (9842ft).  Take in spectacular tandem views of Kanchenjunga to the east and Everest to the west before dropping off into the lush villages of the Tamur River Valley.\r\n\r\nOnce on the river, the whitewater starts out strong, with class 4 and 5 rapids. The rest of the river alternates between intense rapids and stretches of mellow water. Play around in a whitewater kayak, swim, and enjoy the mountains and villages along the way.\r\n\r\nThis is the ultimate trip for those truly wanting an adventure off the beaten path.\r\n\r\n<strong>Please note: </strong>Nepalaya Explorer is currently in the process of assessing the affects of the 2015 earthquakes on the Tamur River area. Please contact Nepalaya Explorer for more information.\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Quick Look\" subtitle=\"Adventure Overview\"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>March - May, Mid October - Mid December\r\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>10 - 12 days\r\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Grade 4\r\n<strong>Grade: </strong>30 ft. per mile\r\n<strong>Distance: </strong>120 km\r\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Appropriate for adventure seekers, rafters, experienced kayakers, and serious outdoor enthusiasts\r\n<strong>Put-in: </strong>Damauli Bridge\r\n<strong>Take-out: </strong>Ghaighat (low water) or Narayanghat (high water)\r\n<strong>Transportation:</strong> Domestic flight from Kathmandu to Biratnagar. (Travelers on a budget can choose to travel by private bus (17 hrs there, 13 hrs return) for a trip price of $1100)\r\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Trekking, rafting, kayaking\r\n<strong>Group Size: </strong>6 - 12 people\r\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>Tented camping\r\n\r\n<strong>2016 Departure Dates: </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>15 March</li>\r\n	<li>15 April</li>\r\n	<li>25 October</li>\r\n	<li>20 November</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Adventure Program\"]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 1: Arrival\" place=\"Kathmandu\"] An Nepalaya Explorer representative will meet you at the airport and escort you to your hotel with our private car.\r\n\r\nIn the afternoon, there is time to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu. At 6 pm, we\'ll meet for a pre-departure briefing in then head off to one of Kathmandu\'s finer and traditional restaurants for a meal together [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2\" place=\"Kathmandu - Biratnagar - Basantapur\"] After breakfast, it\'s time to head off to the airport for a 55-minute flight to Biratnagar. At Biratnagar we meet up with the rafting bus and drive up through the bustling market town of Hile and onto the end of the road at Basantapur. A cozy family-run teahouse is our rest place for the night. In this region, the locals have developed the preparation of <em>thungba</em>, a (millet wine) to a fine art. [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 3 - 6\" place=\"Trek to Dobhan\"]While the S<em>irdhar</em> (head porter) sorts out logistics, and divides the gear, our group prepares for the day ahead.\r\n\r\nThis region is largely unexplored by tourists, and the villages and farms you see along the trail are reminiscent of rural Nepal over the last several hundred years. Our 3 day trek follows a ridge up to a 10,000 ft pass above the sacred lake at Gupha pokhari with magnificent views of Kanchenjuga, Makalu and the Everest welcome you each morning when you wake up and open your tent, before dropping into the lush villages of the Tamur valley providing a truly memorable approach to this classic Himalayan white water descent. Days are long and the trail can be difficult in some places, but with porters carry the gear and Sherpa guides we should all make it to the river intact. Expedition members carry a daypack with a warm set of clothes, water bottle, camera or other must reach items.\r\n\r\nTrekking camps are an extravagant affair with staff preparing well-deserved meals. Before arriving at the put-in in Dobhan, via a descent through a variety of thick rhododendron forest and lush valleys, it is highly recommended that you again sample the local <em>thungba. </em>\r\n\r\nIn Dobhan we make our first riverside camp.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 6 - 10\" place=\"Whitewater Rafting\"] In the morning, the guides sort out the equipment and secure gear into the rafts. After we double check all the nuts and loops, our river guides gather you up and spend the first part of the morning explaining the finer points of paddling, river safety and staying in the raft as it bucks through rapids. For those who missed a point in the previous lesson there is a follow-up on how to swim through whitewater, using your personal flotation device to keep head up and your feet to push off rocks (or pesky kayakers who happen to be surfing in the middle of a rapid). The guides will also teach you what they look out for when they run a river, the innocuous looking rise in the water that hides a hole, or the way you can use a pillow of water rebounding off a rocks to push the raft where you want it.\r\n\r\nAt Dobhan the Tamur and its tributaries drain the snows of Kachenjuga, the third highest peak in the world. Constrained by steep valley walls, it becomes Nepal’s sixth largest river and one of the world’s most renowned remote whitewater expeditions.\r\n\r\nFrom our put-in, we have 120 kilometers of breath-taking river journey through the hearts of eastern part of remote Nepal. With over 100 class 3 and 4+ rapids, Thundering Tamur offers a unique six days of whitewater action with plenty of time to explore untouched hidden side valleys and visit some remote villages, combined with some white-capped mountain view while rafting down on the back round.\r\n\r\nThe massive monsoon floods deposit huge tracks of pure white sand and drifted logs along the river, creating ideal campsites surrounded by lush forest and hillsides terraced. Expedition like this we will have at least one day layover day where we stay at the same river camp for two nights. This days we play lots of games such as KING OF THE JUNGLE!!! Beach Volleyball, Frisbee, Hide and Found and paddle game, sun bathing or just relaxing on a warm beach with good book are favorite activities for the layover day. Our guide is not only guiding raft they are multi talented so make a friend and take a advantage of this layover day to trek to peak or nearby village, or best thing we can you do is to take a part in the kayak workshop the safety boaters offer and this is our Bonus, many of you might have keep in your mind after watching them playing in waves and making some great moves so go for it and we organize kayak clinic trip as well. Evening are spent around the campfire, drinking hot-spiced rum, Raksi (local homemade wine) and getting to know the people on the trip. Food is communally prepared, every day a different raft crew helping with the creation of sumptuous meals. The kitchen becomes one of the main social points on the trip, and without doubt the best place to catch up and talk on the gossip or get to know someone better. “Adventure can change your Life.”[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 9\"] In the middle section, the river opens up and there are beautiful white sandy beaches to camp on and enjoy the sunsets. On the second to last day, the river turns back to the west. This is phenomenal section of whitewater, with over 50 rapids throughout the day. We will scout a few along the way, monster rapids like Ashram and double f#%k. Then, just before our camp on the tributary of the Sun Koshi, we encounter Bad Below, a rapid reminiscent of being flushed down a huge open-air toilet. Emerald green fields are terraced high above the river on the precipitous slopes, curious villagers lining on the suspension bridge are amazed as we plunge through cascading waves and chutes of foam. When the village kids see rafts approaching, they are all keen to get a view of the spectacle and a chance of seeing any carnage with flipped rafts or swimmers [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 10\"] The temple Tribeni Ghat marks the conlfuence of the Tamur with the Sun Koshi. We pass a second Hindu temple, Baraha Chetra, before emerging from the canyon into the Terai. Every year on the day of the full moon in January, thousands of Hindu pilgrims mass here to pay homage to Lord Vishnu. Legend has it that once a demon god inhabited this area and troubled the villagers, holy men and pilgrims. Hearing of this, Lord Vishnu, preserver of the universe, took the form of a pig and slayed the demon in battle. Inside the temple is the pig-headed figure of Lord Vishnu, and the annual Braha festival commemorates his victory. We take the time to explore these holy grounds before jumping back in the rafts for an easy float through one last wave train.\r\n\r\nAfter stripping down the raft and loading the bus, we venture into the town of Chatra to our favorite local restaurant for some good Dhal Bhat, and tuck into a great meal - and of course cold drinks - before we heading either to the airport for our 40 min flight back to Kathmandu or onto the bus for the 15-hr overland journey. [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 11\" place=\"Farewell dinner &amp; preparing for the next adventure\"] Back in Kathmandu, after checking into the hotel, enjoying a long hot shower and shave, and perhaps a bit of sightseeing or shopping, we reunite again with river crew and for a celebration banquet, telling stories and of course planning for our next river adventure. [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 12\" place=\"Return home\"] If you are returning home following your trip, Nepayala Explorer will deliver you back to the Kathmandu International Airport. [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Includes:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Licensed English-speaking local guides and safety kayakers, highly trained and safety certified to international standards in: Rescue 3 WRT, Nepal Red Cross CPR, High Peak First Aid, International Wilderness First-Aid, IRF trained, and highly knowledgable about the local area</li>\r\n	<li>High-quality, ISO certified rafting and kayaking equipment and full personal outfitting, including: paddles, helmets, PFDs (life jackets) dry tops, wetsuits (youth sizes available), dry bags, and pelican boxes for valuables such as cameras</li>\r\n	<li>Two nights at a *** hotel in Kathmandu, one day sightseeing in Kathmandu, airport pickup and drop-off</li>\r\n	<li>Camping accommodation, including: shelters, personal tents, air mattresses, sleeping bags, pillow, picnic umbrella, table and chairs, toilet tents</li>\r\n	<li>Three meals daily: a hearty breakfast, leisurely lunch, and dinner with a complementary glass of wine. While on the river, guides prepare traditional Nepali and western cuisine, made with fresh, organic ingredients.</li>\r\n	<li>Complementary beverages, including bottled water</li>\r\n	<li>Round trip transportation via private car</li>\r\n	<li>River permits</li>\r\n	<li>Village sightseeing</li>\r\n	<li>Adventure Industry standard first aid kits</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Does Not Include:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\r\n	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Alcohol and specialty beverages</li>\r\n	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\r\n	<li>Travel and health insurance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Packing Aid:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your sense of adventure (and humor!)</li>\r\n	<li>River shorts or swim costume</li>\r\n	<li>Chacos or similar sandals that secure your heal (trainers or sneakers are also suitable for rafting)</li>\r\n	<li>Long sleeved shirt to wear under your life vest to keep the sun off, preferably a quick-dry, synthetic fiber</li>\r\n	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\r\n	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\r\n	<li>Sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\r\n	<li>Nalgene or other sturdy water bottle</li>\r\n	<li>Carabiner for fastening water bottle to your boat</li>\r\n	<li>Thermal top - meadium weight to heavyweight Capilene or polypropylene is the best choice</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof sunscreen and lip balm (minimum SPF15)</li>\r\n	<li>Lightweight long trousers</li>\r\n	<li>Lightweight long sleeved shirt</li>\r\n	<li>Fleece jacket or sweater</li>\r\n	<li>Down jacket (nights get cold along the trekking route)</li>\r\n	<li>Ladies, please bring a long skirt or sarong to wear in the company of locals or while visiting holy places</li>\r\n	<li>Shoes or boots for exploring off the river</li>\r\n	<li>Toiletries: toothbrush, toothpaste, biodegradable soap, shampoo, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Moisturizer</li>\r\n	<li>Hand wipes or hand sanitizer</li>\r\n	<li>3-season sleeping bag and thermo rest sleeping mat if you prefer to use your own (we provide a complementary set upon request)</li>\r\n	<li>Travel pillow</li>\r\n	<li>Small pack towel</li>\r\n	<li>Headlamp or hand torch with spare batteries</li>\r\n	<li>Insect repellent</li>\r\n	<li>Any medications you may be taking</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Personal Items:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A book or journal for recording river memories and inspirations</li>\r\n	<li>Sketchpad</li>\r\n	<li>Photographic, GOPRO, or video equipment. We recommend bringing your own waterproof casing and a cleaning kit as we will be camping in the sand. Don\'t forget a spare memory card or plenty of film, as well as spare batteries.</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof disposable camera to document the \"action\" on the raft</li>\r\n	<li>Pocket knife or multi-tool</li>\r\n	<li>iPod or other portable music device (your guide will pack the speakers)</li>\r\n	<li>Binoculars if you are a bird watcher</li>\r\n	<li>In short, we advise you to pack as light as possible, without skimping on the essentials.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Personal Spending:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The only money you will need on the excursion is for meals in town, souvenirs, personal items and the beer kitty for the raft trip if you drink. ATMs are available in larger towns.</li>\r\n	<li>If you wish to pass on a gratuity to your team, we leave this entirely up to you, but kindly suggest that if you do choose to give, give to the group as a whole so that the team can share with those who are working behind the scenes to make your trip complete.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Tamur River Adventure', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'tamur-river-adventure', '', '', '2016-08-07 13:31:25', '2016-08-07 13:31:25', '', 0, 'http://dac.technocreates.net/nepalayaexplorer/?post_type=tours&#038;p=3381', 0, 'tours', '', 0),
(3383, 3, '2016-07-22 14:06:08', '2016-07-22 14:06:08', '[tg_header title=\"Explore the Untouched Nepal\" subtitle=\"Rafting, Kayaking, and Trekking\"]\n\nThe Tamur River adventure combines one of the world’s finest rivers with a world-famous Himalayan trek.\n\nHands down the best multi-sport trip in Nepal, the Tamur River adventure starts with four days of trekking and camping through woodland and meadows, following a ridgeline at around 3000m (9842ft).  Take in spectacular tandem views of Kanchenjunga to the east and Everest to the west before dropping off into the lush villages of the Tamur River Valley.\n\nOnce on the river, the whitewater starts out strong, with class 4 and 5 rapids. The rest of the river alternates between intense rapids and stretches of mellow water. Play around in a whitewater kayak, swim, and enjoy the mountains and villages along the way.\n\nThis is the ultimate trip for those truly wanting an adventure off the beaten path.\n\n<strong>Please note: </strong>Nepalaya Explorer is currently in the process of assessing the affects of the 2015 earthquakes on the Tamur River area. Please contact Nepalaya Explorer for more information.\n\n[tg_header title=\"Quick Look\" subtitle=\"Adventure Overview\"]\n\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>March - May, Mid October - Mid December\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>10 - 12 days\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Grade 4\n<strong>Grade: </strong>30 ft. per mile\n<strong>Distance: </strong>120 km\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Appropriate for adventure seekers, rafters, experienced kayakers, and serious outdoor enthusiasts\n<strong>Put-in: </strong>Damauli Bridge\n<strong>Take-out: </strong>Ghaighat (low water) or Narayanghat (high water)\n<strong>Transportation:</strong> Domestic flight from Kathmandu to Biratnagar. Or, choose to travel b private bus (17 hrs there, 13 hrs return) for a discount of $350\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Trekking, rafting, kayaking\n<strong>Group Size: </strong>6 - 12 people\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>Tented camping\n\n[tg_header title=\"Adventure Program\"]\n\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2: Arrival\" place=\"Kathmandu\"] An Nepalaya Explorer representative will meet you at the airport and escort you to your hotel with our private car.\n\nIn the afternoon, there is time to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu. At 6 pm, we\'ll meet for a pre-departure briefing in then head off to one of Kathmandu\'s finer and traditional restaurants for a meal together [/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2\" place=\"Kathmandu - Biratnagar - Basantapur\"] After breakfast, it\'s time to head off to the airport for a 55-minute flight to Biratnagar. At Biratnagar we meet up with the rafting bus and drive up through the bustling market town of Hile and onto the end of the road at Basantapur. A cozy family-run teahouse is our rest place for the night. In this region, the locals have developed the preparation of <em>thungba</em>, a (millet wine) to a fine art. [/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title=\"Day 3 - 6\" place=\"Trek to Dobhan\"]While the S<em>irdhar</em> (head porter) sorts out logistics, and divides the gear, our group prepares for the day ahead.\n\nThis region is largely unexplored by tourists, and the villages and farms you see along the trail are reminiscent of rural Nepal over the last several hundred years. Our 3 day trek follows a ridge up to a 10,000 ft pass above the sacred lake at Gupha pokhari with magnificent views of Kanchenjuga, Makalu and the Everest welcome you each morning when you wake up and open your tent, before dropping into the lush villages of the Tamur valley providing a truly memorable approach to this classic Himalayan white water descent. Days are long and the trail can be difficult in some places, but with porters carry the gear and Sherpa guides we should all make it to the river intact. Expedition members carry a daypack with a warm set of clothes, water bottle, camera or other must reach items.\n\nTrekking camps are an extravagant affair with staff preparing well-deserved meals. Before arriving at the put-in in Dobhan, via a descent through a variety of thick rhododendron forest and lush valleys, it is highly recommended that you again sample the local <em>thungba. </em>\n\nIn Dobhan we make our first riverside camp.[/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title=\"Day 6 - 10\" place=\"Whitewater Rafting\"] In the morning, the guides sort out the equipment and secure gear into the rafts. After we double check all the nuts and loops, our river guides gather you up and spend the first part of the morning explaining the finer points of paddling, river safety and staying in the raft as it bucks through rapids. For those who missed a point in the previous lesson there is a follow-up on how to swim through whitewater, using your personal flotation device to keep head up and your feet to push off rocks (or pesky kayakers who happen to be surfing in the middle of a rapid). The guides will also teach you what they look out for when they run a river, the innocuous looking rise in the water that hides a hole, or the way you can use a pillow of water rebounding off a rocks to push the raft where you want it.\n\nAt Dobhan the Tamur and its tributaries drain the snows of Kachenjuga, the third highest peak in the world. Constrained by steep valley walls, it becomes Nepal’s sixth largest river and one of the world’s most renowned remote whitewater expeditions.\n\nFrom our put-in, we have 120 kilometers of breath-taking river journey through the hearts of eastern part of remote Nepal. With over 100 class 3 and 4+ rapids, Thundering Tamur offers a unique six days of whitewater action with plenty of time to explore untouched hidden side valleys and visit some remote villages, combined with some white-capped mountain view while rafting down on the back round.\n\nThe massive monsoon floods deposit huge tracks of pure white sand and drifted logs along the river, creating ideal campsites surrounded by lush forest and hillsides terraced. Expedition like this we will have at least one day layover day where we stay at the same river camp for two nights. This days we play lots of games such as KING OF THE JUNGLE!!! Beach Volleyball, Frisbee, Hide and Found and paddle game, sun bathing or just relaxing on a warm beach with good book are favorite activities for the layover day. Our guide is not only guiding raft they are multi talented so make a friend and take a advantage of this layover day to trek to peak or nearby village, or best thing we can you do is to take a part in the kayak workshop the safety boaters offer and this is our Bonus, many of you might have keep in your mind after watching them playing in waves and making some great moves so go for it and we organize kayak clinic trip as well. Evening are spent around the campfire, drinking hot-spiced rum, Raksi (local homemade wine) and getting to know the people on the trip. Food is communally prepared, every day a different raft crew helping with the creation of sumptuous meals. The kitchen becomes one of the main social points on the trip, and without doubt the best place to catch up and talk on the gossip or get to know someone better. “Adventure can change your Life.”[/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title=\"Day 9\"] In the middle section, the river opens up and there are beautiful white sandy beaches to camp on and enjoy the sunsets. On the second to last day, the river turns back to the west. This is phenomenal section of whitewater, with over 50 rapids throughout the day. We will scout a few along the way, monster rapids like Ashram and double f#%k. Then, just before our camp on the tributary of the Sun Koshi, we encounter Bad Below, a rapid reminiscent of being flushed down a huge open-air toilet. Emerald green fields are terraced high above the river on the precipitous slopes, curious villagers lining on the suspension bridge are amazed as we plunge through cascading waves and chutes of foam. When the village kids 