(3438, 3, '2016-08-07 23:35:16', '2016-08-07 23:35:16', '[tg_header title=\"River of Gold\" subtitle=\"(not for the faint-hearted)\"]\r\n\r\nOriginating near Mt. Shisha Pangma in Tibet, the “River of Gold” runs eastward through Nepal draining most of the eastern portion of the Nepal Himalayas. Gathering strength from tributaries draining the highest mountains in the world the whitewater on the Sun Koshi is Biblical. Rapids are huge, and even expedition size rafts disappear into the vastness of crashing waves and rolling, boiling water. Whipped foamy white where narrow gorges constrict the river\'s flow the cataracts are long and powerful. From the put in at Dolalghat to the take out at Chatara in far-eastern Nepal, the warm water of the Sun Koshi surge, snake and wind through 270 km of some of Nepal\'s remotest country side. At the right flow this river journey is an incredible combination of white water, scenery, villages, and truly quiet and introspective evenings on huge sandy beaches along what many people consider to be one of the world\'s 10 classic river journeys.\r\n\r\nTo run the Sun Koshi just a month before the end of the Monsoon must rate as one of life\'s most exhilarating experiences. We are the only company who loves and operates on the Sun Koshi this time of the year with our fully safety and professional crew.  At this time of the year the river is high and wild, and definitely not for the faint-hearted. This is big volume whitewater at its best. Swept along by the pulsing waters we\'re soon maneuvering through boiling narrow channels and dodging obstacles. The river dances through corridors of lush forest then accelerates through leaping waves and roaring drops. There are dozens of adrenaline pumping rapids, and miles of calmer water to reflect on the beauty of this remote area and totally unwind.\r\n\r\nThis is the longest river trip offered in Nepal, carving through the beautiful Mahabharat Range on its meandering way from the put in to the take out at Chatara, far down on the Gangetic Plain. It\'s quite an experience to begin a river trip, barely 60 kms from the Tibetan border, and end the trip looking down the hot, dusty gun barrel of the North India Plain just eight days later. The Sun Koshi starts off fairly relaxed, with class 2 and small class 3 rapids to warm up on during the first couple of days. Savvy guides will take this opportunity to get the teams working together, as on the third day the rapids become more powerful and frequent, with high water trips finding themselves astonished at just how big a wave in a river can get. While the lower sections of large volume rivers are usually rather flat, the Sun Koshi reserves some of its biggest and best rapids for the last days.\r\n\r\nBlack hole, Meat grinder, High Anxiety, Jaws, Harkapur II, Roller Coaster, Dead Men Eddy and The Big Dipper are only some of the rapids that have earned their names and reputations from previous expeditions. Days of constant white water, time spent exploring villages, jungle, and some of the small Hindu temples along the way make this an unbeatable river expedition.\r\n\r\n<strong>Canyoning including: </strong>The Sun Koshi river offers one of the great Waterfall on our river journey, there for we are the only company who offers day Canyoning trip to give value of this Mother Nature gift and have fun with warm water abseiling down, jumping on a pond and sliding down in middle of nowhere, surrounded by thick jungle, quietness and lush vegetation. Your raft guide is multi knowledge who turn into a Canyoning guide ride away and abseil you down with our State Of Art gear that secretly carry by them. This is our complementary surprise package so please have fun.\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Quick Look\" subtitle=\"Adventure Overview\"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>May - mid June, mid August - October\r\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>10 days (8 river days)\r\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Grade 4- / 4+\r\n<strong>Distance: </strong>270 km\r\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Adventure Seekers, Rafters, Expert Kayakers, Outdoor Enthusiasts\r\n<strong>Put-in: </strong>Dolalghat\r\n<strong>Take-out: </strong>Chatara\r\n<strong>Transportation:</strong> Private bus from Kathmandu (2 1/2 hrs to put-in, 13 hrs back from take-out) Option to upgrade to domestic flight from Biratnagar to Kathmandu ($150 airfare not included in price)\r\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Rafting, Canyoning\r\n<strong>Minimum Group Size: </strong>6 people (discounts available for larger groups)\r\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>Tented camping\r\n\r\n<strong>2016 Departure Dates: </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>15 May</li>\r\n	<li>1 June</li>\r\n	<li>15 August</li>\r\n	<li>5 September</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Adventure Program\"]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 1: Arrival\" place=\"Kathmandu\"]\r\n\r\nAn Nepalaya Explorer representative will meet you at the airport and escort you to your hotel with our private car.\r\n\r\nIn the afternoon, there is time to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu. At 6 pm, we\'ll meet for a pre-departure briefing in then head off to one of Kathmandu\'s finer and traditional restaurants for a meal together.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2\" place=\"Kathmandu City Excursion\"]\r\n\r\nTime to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu. Nepalaya Explore provide you multi knowledge guide. Walking around this ancient city is like being in the world\'s biggest outdoor museum! We recommend a good guide book (cheaply available in Kathmandu\'s many book shops) and then grabbing either a taxi or rickshaw or heading off on foot to visit some of the incredible temples, stupas, and squares that make up this most vibrant of capitals. From observing prayer wheels turning at the Buddhist stupa of Buddhnath, to perhaps gaining a glimpse of the Living Goddess in Durbar Square, there are endless ways to pass the day. A great way to finish it off is with a cold drink on one of the many terrace cafes people watching. Kathmandu has more eccentric characters per square km than any other country on Earth. At 6pm this evening we\'ll have a pre-departure briefing in then head off to one of Kathmandu\'s finer restaurants for a meal together.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 3 - 9\" place=\"Monsoon Blast\"]\r\n\r\nAfter a hearty breakfast at finer Restaurant it\'s time to push the herd north towards the big river. The put in for the Sun Kosi is only two hours away by bus through the ancient city of Baktapur and out of the Kathmandu valley to the village of Dolalghat. On a clear day the views of the Himalayas and Mt. Everest are incredible and we stop for short photo shoot. At our put in point we sort equipment and inflate the rafts. The guides tie all the equipment into the rafts, which is quite a thing to witness. Twenty years of running rivers has taught us a lot, not the least of which is how to tie a load so it stays put no matter what.\r\n\r\nA raft trip down the Sun Koshi isn\'t just a vacation. It’s an education. Our river guides spend the first part of the morning explaining the finer points on how to paddle through whitewater and stay in the raft as it bucks and contorts through rapids. For those who missed a point in the previous lesson there is a lesson on how to swim through whitewater, using your flotation device to keep your head up and your feet to push off rocks or pesky kayakers who happen to be surfing in the middle of a rapid. The guides will also teach you what they look out for when they run a river, the innocuous looking rise in the water that hides a hole, or the way you can use a pillow of water rebounding off a rock to push the raft where you want it. Whitewater rafts are amazingly versatile and stable crafts, and in the care of an expert raft guide it is possible to run challenging lines safely and confidently. Your guide is a professional, someone who has devoted their life to learning and running rivers. Under his or her careful indoctrination the raft crew learns how to work as a team, practicing on the numerous smaller rapids we encounter on the first two days of the river. By the time we get to the really big rapids the crews will be working together with the timing and precision of a Thamel nightclub act. It\'s a good thing too, because the first time you line up above big water class IV rapid you\'re not going to believe what you see, hear, and feel. The water above a big rapid is as soothing and quiet as a children\'s story, and it\'s not until you look down into the churning, digesting, gut-twisting white abyss that you realize the story is written by the Brothers Grimm. Gravity seems like a seductive and cruel mistress, pulling us into something we want. We drift smoothly along and watch as our fate is sealed. the watery conveyor belt undulating and throbbing; finally giving way to the liquid cheese grater attachment of life\'s Quisinart. Most people find that time slows down and fear vanishes, replaced by a primal resignation and a sharpening of all senses to a point usually only attained during an automobile crash. The heart-shaking roar of whitewater becomes dim, like a background symphony heard through the cheap paper walls of some sleazy budget hotel. Now this is living!\r\n\r\nFrom Dolalghat we have 270 blissfully motor-free kilometers before we hit the next road. 270 kilometers of living for no other purpose other than to see how much fun we can have. Life is reduced to eat, sleep and play. In accomplishing these things, you\'ll be amazed at how much you can learn, and more importantly, how much you\'ll forget. In no time at all the amalgamation of all your concerns will seem distant, unimportant and eventually, unworthy of your attention.\r\n\r\nMost of the rapids on the Sun Koshi are formed by monsoon debris brought in by side streams and loose rock fall. These rapids change from year to year depending on the severity of the monsoon rains. After stopping at Tokshel Harkapur and spending time checking out this porter town we drift down to a rapid called Harkapur 2. Pulling over to the left to camp for the evening it is interesting to go down and look at the rapid and contemplate the start of the next day. Harkapur 2 becomes the main topic of conversation that night. There is a large rockfall on the right and the river is further constricted on the left by a huge debris slide! Boulders from the slide have washed into the middle of the rapid forming large ledge drops and holes. Harkapur 2 is always an interesting rapid and there is plenty more to come. A few kilometers downstream watch out for the famous Dudh Koshi, the river of milk, which tumbles down from Mount Everest. We recommend a sacrificial swimmer out of the raft here to appease the Gods. The Dudh Koshi is a lot cooler than the Sun Koshi. Below the suspension bridge is a small rapid that is followed by Jaws. Sculptured into the rock on the left side of the river is a huge eddy that has a dubious reputation of collecting most things that float downstream!\r\n\r\nCamping on the Sun Koshi is awesome. The massive floods of the monsoon deposit huge tracks of pure white sand along the river creating ideal campsites. We will have at least one layover day where we stay at the same river camp for two nights. KING OF THE JUNGLE!!! Beach Volleyball, sand sculpture, Paddle game, Hide and Found, Frisbee, sun bathing or just relaxing on a warm beach with a good book are favorite activities for the layover day. You can also take advantage of the layover day to trek to a peak or nearby village, or take part in the kayak workshop the safety boater’s offer. Evenings are spent around the campfire, drinking hot-spiced rum and getting to know the people on the trip. Food is communally prepared, every day a different raft crew helping with the creation of sumptuous meals. The kitchen becomes one of the main social points on the trip, and without a doubt the best place to catch up on the latest gossip or get to know someone better.\" Make a Friendship that could last for a Lifetime as a good friend or Life Partner.”\r\n\r\nThe Jungle Corridor is an outrageous section of rapids in a hard rock canyon with tropical forest right down to the river. At the end of the Jungle Corridor a series of waterfalls cascade in from both banks so keep your soap and shampoo (biodegradable of course!) handy for a really refreshing shower.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 10: Arrival\" place=\"The Quick Sripper\"]\r\n\r\nThe last big rapid of the trip is called The Big Dipper. Tie your shorts on tight, because the other name for this rapid is The Quick Stripper. We needn\'t elaborate. If we all make it through this one with our dignity intact, it\'s a quiet cruise down the confluence with the Tamur and Arun and the beginning of the Sapta Koshi, or the Seven Rivers.\r\n\r\nThe confluence is marked by the temple Tribeni Ghat. We pass a an even larger Hindu temple, Baraha Chetra, before emerging from the canyon into the Terai. Every year on the day of the full moon in January, thousands of Hindu pilgrims mass here to pay homage to Lord Vishnu. Legend has it that once a demon god inhabited this area and troubled the villagers, holy men and pilgrims. Hearing of this, Lord Vishnu, preserver of the universe, took the form of a pig and slayed the demon in battle. Inside the temple is the pig-headed figure of Lord Vishnu, and the annual Braha festival commemorates his victory. We take the time to explore these holy grounds before jumping back in the rafts for an easy float through one last wave train.\r\n\r\nBy noon we have reached the takeout and all the expedition equipment is cleaned, sun-dried, and broken down then loaded on top of our private bus. From the takeout it is a 2 hour drive, then a 55-minute flight back to KTM and a welcome hot shower. The mountain views on a clear day are outstanding as the flight goes right along the main Himalayas.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 11:\" place=\"Return Home\"]\r\n\r\nAfter a leisurely breakfast, an Nepalaya Explorer representative takes you to the airport for your return flight.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Add-on Option:\" place=\"Safari\"]\r\n\r\nStaying at the luxurious Temple Tiger Camp is a great way to cap your trip down the Sun Koshi. Set in the heart of the Royal Chitwan National Park, the lodge offers unparalleled opportunities to see the prolific bird life, not to mention occasional sightings of the Royal Bengal Tiger, rhinos and an amazing array of other wildlife. Naturalists are on hand with their seemingly endless supply of knowledge to answer your queries regarding all the species of animal in the park. The lodge is made entirely of local materials and blends in beautifully with the environment. There is a range of activities to enjoy, from elephant safaris to jungle walks, to just relaxing in the serene surroundings of the Lodge. Meals are all-inclusive and are a combination of Western and Nepali dishes. Since you do have to book in advance we strongly recommend that you try and think how you will feel at the end of the river journey and decide if returning to Kathmandu will really be the option that you will want! On day thirteen we transfer you to Meghauly Airport (about 2 ½ hours away) where you will meet with your return flight to Kathmandu. That afternoon we suggest that you spend some time doing some well deserved retail therapy. A group farewell dinner is always welcomed and it is a final chance to relive the previous two weeks with people that do believe you when you explain just how big that waves and hole was!\r\n\r\nThere is a variety of accommodation available at the Lodge, so please inquire about pricing.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Includes:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Licensed English-speaking local guides and safety kayakers, highly trained and safety certified to international standards in: Rescue 3 WRT, Nepal Red Cross CPR, High Peak First Aid, International Wilderness First-Aid, IRF trained, and highly knowledgable about the local area</li>\r\n	<li>High-quality, ISO certified rafting and kayaking equipment and full personal outfitting, including: paddles, helmets, PFDs (life jackets) dry tops, wetsuits (youth sizes available), dry bags, and pelican boxes for valuables such as cameras</li>\r\n	<li>Two nights at a *** hotel in Kathmandu, one day sightseeing in Kathmandu, airport pickup and drop-off</li>\r\n	<li>Camping accommodation, including: shelters, personal tents, air mattresses, sleeping bags, pillow, picnic umbrella, table and chairs, toilet tents</li>\r\n	<li>Three meals daily: a hearty breakfast, leisurely lunch, and dinner with a complementary glass of wine. While on the river, guides prepare traditional Nepali and western cuisine, made with fresh, organic ingredients.</li>\r\n	<li>Complementary beverages, including bottled water</li>\r\n	<li>Round trip transportation via private car</li>\r\n	<li>River permits</li>\r\n	<li>Village sightseeing</li>\r\n	<li>Adventure Industry standard first aid kits</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Does Not Include:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\r\n	<li>Unrelated transportation, visas, travel documents, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Alcohol and junk food</li>\r\n	<li>Bottled mineral water</li>\r\n	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\r\n	<li>Travel and health insurance</li>\r\n	<li>Kayaks - can be rented upon request. Please inquire.</li>\r\n	<li>Photos - Professional trip photos may be available at a small additional charge. Please inquire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Packing Aid:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your sense of adventure (and humor!)</li>\r\n	<li>River shorts or swim costume</li>\r\n	<li>Chacos or similar sandals that secure your heal (trainers or sneakers are also suitable for rafting)</li>\r\n	<li>Long sleeved shirt to wear under your life vest to keep the sun off, preferably a quick-dry, synthetic fiber</li>\r\n	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\r\n	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\r\n	<li>Sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\r\n	<li>Nalgene or other sturdy water bottle</li>\r\n	<li>Carabiner for fastening water bottle to your boat</li>\r\n	<li>Thermal top - meadium weight to heavyweight Capilene or polypropylene is the best choice</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof sunscreen and lip balm (minimum SPF15)</li>\r\n	<li>Lightweight long trousers</li>\r\n	<li>Lightweight long sleeved shirt</li>\r\n	<li>Fleece jacket or sweater</li>\r\n	<li>Ladies, please bring a long skirt or sarong to wear in the company of locals or while visiting holy places</li>\r\n	<li>Shoes or boots for exploring off the river</li>\r\n	<li>Toiletries: toothbrush, toothpaste, biodegradable soap, shampoo, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Moisturizer</li>\r\n	<li>Hand wipes or hand sanitizer</li>\r\n	<li>3-season sleeping bag and thermo rest sleeping mat if you prefer to use your own (we provide a complementary set upon request)</li>\r\n	<li>Travel pillow</li>\r\n	<li>Small pack towel</li>\r\n	<li>Headlamp or hand torch with spare batteries</li>\r\n	<li>Insect repellent</li>\r\n	<li>Any medications you may be taking</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Personal Items:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A book or journal for recording river memories and inspirations</li>\r\n	<li>Sketchpad</li>\r\n	<li>Photographic, GOPRO, or video equipment. We recommend bringing your own waterproof casing and a cleaning kit as we will be camping in the sand. Don\'t forget a spare memory card or plenty of film, as well as spare batteries.</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof disposable camera to document the \"action\" on the raft</li>\r\n	<li>Pocket knife or multi-tool</li>\r\n	<li>iPod or other portable music device (your guide will pack the speakers)</li>\r\n	<li>Binoculars if you are a bird watcher</li>\r\n	<li>In short, we advise you to pack as light as possible, without skimping on the essentials.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Personal Spending:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The only money you will need on the excursion is for meals in town, souvenirs, personal items and the beer kitty for the raft trip if you drink. ATMs are available in larger towns.</li>\r\n	<li>If you wish to pass on a gratuity to your team, we leave this entirely up to you, but kindly suggest that if you do choose to give, give to the group as a whole so that the team can share with those who are working behind the scenes to make your trip complete.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Sun Koshi Rafting Adventure', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '3410-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-08-07 23:35:16', '2016-08-07 23:35:16', '', 3410, 'http://dac.technocreates.net/nepalayaexplorer/2016/08/07/3410-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3439, 3, '2016-08-09 01:12:16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '[tg_header title=\"A Little Slice of Paradice\" subtitle=\"learn the art of canyoning\"]\r\n\r\nShort introduction on Canyoning HERE.\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Quick Look\" subtitle=\"Adventure Overview\"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>March - June, August - November\r\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>5 days\r\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Moderate\r\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Adventure Seekers, Outdoor Enthusiasts, Aspiring Guides\r\n<strong>Location: </strong>Charaundi &amp; Jalberi\r\n<strong>Transportation:</strong> Bus from Kathmandu (approx. 3 hr)\r\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Canyoning\r\n<strong>Group Size: </strong>\r\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>N/A\r\n\r\n<strong>2016 Departure Dates: </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>7, 10, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, 28 March</li>\r\n	<li>3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24 April</li>\r\n	<li>4, 7, 10, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, 28, 31 May</li>\r\n	<li>3, 6, 10, 15, 20 June</li>\r\n	<li>25, 30 August</li>\r\n	<li>3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 25, 28 September</li>\r\n	<li>1, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 22, 25, 28, 31 October</li>\r\n	<li>2, 5, 8, 11, 14, 17, 22, 25 November</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Adventure Program\"]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 1: Introduction\" place=\"Introduction to Charaundi\"]\r\n\r\nFirst thing in the morning, we drive to Charaundi, approximately 3 hrs from Kathmandu.. The Charaundi waterfall is a small volume cascade, and offers a comfortable location for learning the basics of canyoning before we head to Jalbire to put our new skills to serious use.\r\n\r\nCanyoning is full body and mind experience. After a short hike to the canyoning site, the course begins by playing with ropes, checking out the location, and getting to know the gear and the team with giving extra high Respect for nature power. This day we learn a number of useful knots, natural anchors, abseiling technique, belay, and water safety. Throughout the run down the canyon, we also learn to understand and respect the power of nature.  Half-way through the canyon, we stop for a rest and a picnic lunch. At 4pm, we return to our campsite on the bank of the Trisuli River and enjoy dinner around the campfire under the Himalayan starry sky.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2\" place=\"Mastering Charaundi\"]\r\n\r\nWe begin our day with morning yoga. Increased flexibility will help our bodies perform better, and be less prone to soreness and injury.\r\n\r\nAfter a hearty and leisurely breakfast, we spend an hour or so at the campsite before heading to the canyon. Here, the instructor gives covers safety briefings, and some nuances of working with clients. Next, you learn how to instruct clients to abseil in a waterfall, how to belay, and learn important safety tips. Along the hike upstream through the canyon, the first thing we do is check the water level for any change from the night before, set anchor and repeat and refresh the course from yesterday. We lunch again in the canyon, and continue downstream before heading for camp around 4 pm.\r\n\r\nWe  enjoy dinner around the campfire and end the day with a briefing. Depending on how the class has progressed, the instructor decides whether to advance to Jalbire on the following day or to spend one last day at Charaundi.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 3\" place=\"Jalberi Advanced Course\"]\r\n\r\nAfter breakfast, we drive to Jalberi (approx. 1 hr). A 30 minute hike brings us face-to-face with the 130 meter waterfall. After setting anchor, we start by sliding or jumping into the pristine pool below. Today, this high-volume canyon offers many challenges. Canyoning carries with it inherent risks, and the Jalberi canyon is high and steep. Safety is our first priority, and we are careful at every step.\r\n\r\nWe begin with practicing abseiling, sliding, jumping, scrambling, climbing, and swimming. Trainees will take turns leading the canyoning expedition down the series of waterfalls.\r\n\r\nWe break for lunch at midday, and in the evening return to set camp in the village of Jalberi. [/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 4\" place=\"Jalberi Advanced Course\"]\r\n\r\nThis day is all about doing things on your own. Trainees are in charge for the day, leading everything  anchor setup to rescue scenarios for potential clients who can\'t manage the abseil on their own. The instructor observes closely, offering tips, averting mistakes, and offering feedback.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 5\" place=\"130 Meter Mission\"]\r\n\r\nThis morning after breakfast, we prepare for the 1 1/2 hr. hike that will take us to the top of the 130 meter Jalberi waterfall.  From here, we descend a series of cascades. The instructor assesses the trainees\' skills in anchoring, safety, interaction with clients, rescue, abseiling, and top and bottom belay. Trainees who pass the assessment may be accepted to the Nepalaya Explorer team. Following our descent, we enjoy lunch at Jalberi village, then return to Kathmandu or continue onward to your next adventure.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Includes:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>State-of-the-art, international name-brand ISO-certified canyoning euipment, including wetsuit, specialized harness with PVC slider seat, PFD, helmet, splash top, ropes, carabiners, and figure eights.</li>\r\n	<li>Licensed professional English-speaking local guides, highly trained and certified to national and international standards in canyoning techniques, advanced rope work, Swift Water Rescue 3, Nepal Red Cross CPR, and wilderness first aid</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch and beverages</li>\r\n	<li>Round trip transportation</li>\r\n	<li>Adventure industry standard first aid kit</li>\r\n	<li>Camping equipment</li>\r\n	<li>Sleeping bag &amp; mat (upon request)</li>\r\n	<li>3 meals daily</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Does Not Include:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\r\n	<li>Unrelated transportation, visas, travel documents, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Alcohol and junk food</li>\r\n	<li>Bottled mineral water</li>\r\n	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\r\n	<li>Personal travel and health insurance</li>\r\n	<li>Kayaks - can be rented upon request. Please inquire.</li>\r\n	<li>Photos - Professional trip photos may be available at a small additional charge. Please inquire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Packing Aid:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Shorts</li>\r\n	<li>Swim Suit</li>\r\n	<li>Chacos or similar sport sandals that secure your heal</li>\r\n	<li>Track pants (comfortable, loose-fitting, preferably synthetic)</li>\r\n	<li>Fleece or other thermal top</li>\r\n	<li>Jacket (waterproof shell)</li>\r\n	<li>Socks</li>\r\n	<li>Hiking boots</li>\r\n	<li>Warm hat (in cooler seasons)</li>\r\n	<li>Towel</li>\r\n	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\r\n	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\r\n	<li>Sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof sunscreen and lip balm (minimum SPF15)</li>\r\n	<li>Any medications you may be taking</li>\r\n	<li>Sleeping bag (if you don\'t have your own, we can provide you with a complementary bag)</li>\r\n	<li>Personal first aid kit</li>\r\n	<li>Water bottle</li>\r\n	<li>Waterproof camera or GOPRO</li>\r\n	<li>A little cash for treats and tips</li>\r\n</ul>', 'North Putao', '', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2016-08-09 01:12:17', '2016-08-09 01:12:17', '', 0, 'http://dac.technocreates.net/nepalayaexplorer/?post_type=tours&#038;p=3439', 0, 'tours', '', 0),
