(3593, 1, '2017-03-22 07:38:47', '2017-03-22 07:38:47', '[tg_header title=\"Everest base camp \" subtitle=\"Top of the World\"]\r\n\r\nWithout a doubt, the Everest Base Camp trek is an adventure of a lifetime, a journey for those whose dreams soar higher than even the clouds. Miles from cars, roads, and modern conveniences, you\'ll satiate your spirit with natural beauty and stretch your personal endurance beyond what you believed possible. The adventure begins in ancient Kathmandu, where you\'ll acclimate to Nepal and explore the city at your leisure, while perhaps making a few last minute preparations for your adventure.\r\n\r\nYour trek to the Everest Base Camp (5,364m or over 3.5 miles!) will bring you to the foot of the world\'s tallest mountain, along suspension bridges spanning chasms of thin air, through hidden Buddhist monasteries, and into the heart of the warm, rugged Sherpa culture. As you travel alongside thrill seekers and photographers from around the globe, you will spy Cho Oyu, Lhotse, Nuptse Ama Dablam and Makalu - three of Earth\'s 10 tallest peaks.\r\n\r\nAt night, you will rest easy in cozy teahouses, knowing that Nepalaya Explorer\'s experienced guides and porters are there to ensure a safe, enjoyable, fascinating experience. You\'ll support local economies, discover hidden strengths, and make friends and memories that will last a lifetime.\r\n\r\nWhat are you waiting for?\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Quick Look\" subtitle=\"Adventure Overview\"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>March - May, September - December\r\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>15 days\r\n<strong>Distance: </strong>180 km\r\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Moderate\r\n<strong>Trip Grade:</strong> Level 3 - Medium\r\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Adventure Seekers, Trekkers, Outdoor Enthusiasts\r\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Trekking\r\n<strong>Highlights: </strong>Mt. Everest, Amadablam, Lhotse, Nuptse, Pumori, &amp; more\r\n<strong>Max. Altitude: </strong>5554 meters<strong>\r\nTransportation: </strong>Domestic Flight (Kathmandu - Lukla - Kathmandu)\r\n<strong>Accommodation: </strong>Guesthouse<strong>\r\nBegin &amp; End: </strong>Kathmandu\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Adventure Program\"]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 1: Arrival\" place=\"Kathmandu\"] An Nepalaya Explorer representative will meet you at the airport and escort you to your hotel with our private car.\r\n\r\nIn the afternoon, there is time to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu.\r\n\r\nIn the evening, at a welcome dinner at a traditional Nepali restaurant, you will enjoy a cultural program, meet your expedition leader and crew and, receive your Itinerary Logbook, and go over the details of the trip ahead.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 2\" place=\"Kathmandu City Excursion\"]\r\n\r\nTime to face the hustle of this amazing city and explore Kathmandu in the company of your knowledgeable Nepalaya Explorer guide. Walking around this ancient city is like being in the world\'s biggest outdoor museum. We recommend choosing a good guide book (available at a reasonable price in Kathmandu\'s many book shops), then grabbing a taxi or rickshaw, or heading off on foot to visit some of the temples, stupas, and squares that make up this vibrant capital city. From observing prayer wheels turning at the Buddhist stupa of Buddhnath, to perhaps gaining a glimpse of the Living Goddess in Durbar Square, there are endless ways to pass the day. A great way to finish it off is with a cold drink on one of the many terrace cafes. There will also be time to pick up any last minute trekking gear.\r\n\r\n<strong>Please Note: </strong>Many historic monuments are currently undergoing repairs following damage caused by the 2015 earthquake.[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 3\" place=\"Kathmandu - Lukla - Phakding (2,652m / 8,700 ft)\"]\r\n\r\nAfter breakfast, we embark for the KTM domestic terminal to catch an early morning flight to Lukla (2,800m/9,186ft), a gateway destination to our our trek. After a40 minute flight over the breathtaking green and white mountains, we reach the Tenzing-Hillary Airport at Lukla. This is one of the most beautiful air routes in the world, culminating in a dramatic landing on a hillside surrounded by high mountains peaks. Upon arrival at Lukla, we meet our remaining crew members and after some packing and arrangements, we begin our trek through the prosperous village of Lukla. To assist with acclimatization, we hike just a short way this first day, to the village of Phakding. Curious trekkers may wish to make a side trip to a nearby monastery en-route.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>3 - 4 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Phakding<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 4\" place=\"Phakding - Namche Bazaar (3440m / 11,280 ft)\"]\r\n\r\nWalking through a beautiful pine forest, the track leads us along the Dudh Koshi River. We cross numerous suspension bridges, including the famous Hillary Suspension Bridge. We catch sight of the glistening Mt. Thamserku (6618 m) and continue onward through the settlements of Benkar, Chumoa,  and Monjo, and pass the check post marking the entrance to Sagarmatha National Park.\r\n\r\nThe trail climbs through forests and across bridges until we reach the confluence of the Dudh Koshi and Bhote Koshi rivers. After a long, steep ascent, we are rewarded with our first sighting of Mt. Everest, peering over the Lhotse-Nuptse ridge. We stop at Chautara to admire the view, then continue onward another hour and a half before reaching Namche Bazaar, the primary trading centre of this region, and our stop for the night.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>5 - 6 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Namche Bazaar<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 5: Acclimatization\" place=\"Namche Bazaar (3,440m / 11,284ft)\"]\r\n\r\nThis is our scheduled \'acclimatization\' day. Health experts recommend staying active during the acclimatization, so we recommend choosing between a hike to Thame, visiting Khunde, or exploring in and around Namche Bazaar.\r\n\r\nNamche Bazzar is the centre of the Everest (Khumbu) region and boasts government offices, ATMs, Internet cafes, shops, restaurants, a bakery, and a colorful market each Friday evening and Saturday. If we trek a few hundred vertical feet during the day, it will help us to properly acclimatize. Your guide will accompany you to the Visitors\' Center near the headquarters of the Sagarmatha National Park to see exhibits dedicated to the first ascents of Mt. Everest, Sherpa culture and the plant and animal life of the Everest region. We can also take an interesting side trip up to Khumjung and the Hillary School.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>variable\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Namche Bazaar<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 6\" place=\"Namche Bazaar - Tengboche (3,870m / 12,694ft)\"]\r\n\r\nAfter breakfast in Namche, we start our trek towards Tengboche enjoying superb view of Mt. Everest, Nuptse, Lhotse, Ama Dablam and close up view of Thamserku. Our trek follows on the gradual trail with few ups and downs overlooking magnificent view of the great Himalaya. Along the way we can spot wild lives like pheasant, musk deer, or a herd of Himalayan Thar. The trail goes gradually down up to Kayangjuma. The path eventually reaches Sansa which is the major trail junction to Gokyo valley and Everest Base Camp. The track then follows through the pine forests and after we cross the prayer flags festooned bridge over Dudh Koshi River, we reach Phunki Thenga, a small settlement with a couple of teahouses and a small army post amidst the alpine woods. After having a relaxed lunch at Phunki Thenga we then have a little tough climb steep up through the pine forests while before we reach Tengboche. Tengboche is a great place for close up views of Ama-Dablam, Nuptse, and Everest and it has a biggest Buddhist Monastery all over in Khumbu region. We pay our visit to the monastery the same day at around 3 p.m. to witness the ceremony in the principal and popular monastery of Everest region.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>5 - 6 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Tengboche<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 7\" place=\"Tengboche - Dingboche (3,870m / 12,694ft)\"]\r\n\r\nWith mountains at its backdrop, the monastery at Tengboche looks more spectacular in the morning. At this juncture, we can take pictures of the monastery and the scenery around and as usual starts the day journey. We choose the upper trail for better views on the way to Pangboche village. We pass through several Chortens and Mani walls and small villages. The place where we stop for lunch not only serves delicious food but also allows a fantastic close-up view of Mt Ama Dablam. In the afternoon, we walk north to Pheriche or take the eastward trail beneath the towering north face of Mt Ama Dablam. From here onwards, the walk is fairly moderate as we enter the Imja Valley. The valley gradually unfolds as we approach the confluence of the Lobuche River. We descend into the river and begin the last and steepest climb of the day up to Dingboche. On arrival at Dingboche, we will see beautiful array of fields enclosed by stone walls to protect barley, buckwheat and potatoes from the cold winds and grazing animals. Overnight at Dingboche.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>5 - 6 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Dingboche<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 8\" place=\"Dingboche - Duglha (4,600m / 15,090ft)\"]\r\n\r\nWe start the day with a climb to Duglha through the Khumbu Khola valley. The walk along the arid terrace is rewarding with awesome views of mountains on all sides. As we come to a yak herder\'s place called Dusa, the valley begins to narrow and we continue through Phulung Karpo, the camp site of the first successful Everest Expedition in 1953. Above Phulung Karpo is Chola Lake. As we move on, the majestic view of Mt. Pumori (7138 m/ 23418 ft) comes into view. As the trail descends and curves, Mt. Pumori disappears from view and we come across a roaring stream. After crossing a small wooden bridge, we ascend to Duglha. We can see the tip of Mt Nuptse from here as well as Mt Cholatse, Mt Thamserku, and several other magnificent peaks. Spending a night in Duglha is ideal for acclimatization purposes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>3 - 4 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Duglha<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 9\" place=\"Duglha - Lobuche (4,940m / 16,207ft)\"]\r\n\r\nBeyond Duglha, we climb up the steep terminal moraine of the Khumbu Glacier. We pass through boulder-strewn slopes as we ascend Chupki Lhara, an eerie ridge top with dramatic mountain views. At the top of the ridge, we will find an array of stones with prayer flags used as memorials to Scott Fischer (American mountaineer) and 10 times Everest submitter Babu Chiri Sherpa (a Nepali mountain guide) who perished on a mission to climb Everest. As the trail drops to the Khumbu Glacier moraine, we find ourselves facing several great peaks - Khumbutse, Lingtren, Pumori and Mahalangur Himal. We are now in the vicinity of Everest but the great mountain still remains elusive. Mt Nuptse towers to the right as the trail crosses the Khumbu Glacier. As we pass along a murmuring stream leaving the Khumbu Glacier behind, we now begin to feel a little out of breath due to high altitude.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>2 - 4 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Lobuche<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 10\" place=\"Lobuche - Gorak Shep (5170m / 16,961ft) - Everest Base Camp (5364,/\"]\r\n\r\nThe trail to Gorak Shep goes ahead through the lateral moraine of the Khumbu Glacier. We pass through the pyramid sign post. Ahead on the trail we see crest of north ridge of Everest along with Mt. Pumori, Mt. Mahalangur, Mt. Lingtern, Mt. Khumbutse, Mt. Nuptse, etc. A small ascent would take us to Thangma Riju from where we perceive 360 degree vista of snowy mountains. Climbing steeply up to the top through the torrent of Changri Glacier, we catch our first glimpse of Kala Patthar, a grey-green knoll beneath the Mt. Pumori. As we reach Gorak Shep, we will find snow-capped mountains looming all around us including the top of the world - Mt. Everest. After a brief lunch and rest, we take the trail to Everest Base Camp through the once vast Gorak Shep Lake. Continuing straight ahead, we come through the Indian army mountaineers\' memorials. Only upon reaching the Everest Base Camp do we really appreciate the Everest climbers who brave the hazardous route through the Khumbu icefall. Mountaineer\'s tents stand out in bright colors against the monotony of gray surroundings (especially in the spring). Nuptse, Khumbuste and Pumori are the mountains we can view from the base camp. Everest actually is not visible from here. By now we have met the ultimate objective of our trip.\r\nHowever, the sunset view from Kala Patthar is more admirable than the sunrise view, so it is suggested to visit Kala Patthar today during sunset. As the setting sun\'s rays strike the snow capped mountains the resulting scenery is indescribable. For those trekkers who wish to continue to Kala Patthar, our guides and Sherpas coordinate in hiking to Kala Patthar for amazing sunset view today rather than waiting until the next day.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>8 - 9 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Gorak Shep<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 11\" place=\"Gorak Shep - Kala Patthar - Pheriche (4,280m / 14,070ft)\"]\r\n\r\nToday is the climax of our trip. We start early in the morning to catch the dramatic views from Kala Patthar witnessing the first light of day shining on Mount Everest. However, we need to get prepared for an early morning, dark and cold temperature (-10 to -14 C) departure beforehand. Further, there is always the potential for chilly wind which is quite common. Familiar peaks such as Lingtren, Khumbutse, Changtse tower to the east even as Everest begins to reveal itself emerging between the west shoulder crest and Nuptse. During the ascent to Kala Patthar, we can pause to catch our breath at several outstanding view points to snap pictures. After several hours of an ascent, we reach Kala Patthar. From this juncture, we scramble to climb the rocky outcrop near to the summit marked by cairns and prayer flags. As we reach the top, we sit on the Kala Patthar where rocks our eyes taking unbelievable Himalayan Panorama, wandering from one mighty massif to another. We take as many pictures as we can and take the in view with our mind\'s eye to last lifetime. On being back to Gorak Shep, we have breakfast and wait other participants to return back. Those participants who will visit Everest Base Camp today will have early breakfast to start early as Everest base camp hike takes longer time (4-5 hrs) than the Kala Patthar hike. Upon return back to Gorak Shep, the group will have lunch together; and afternoon time is taken to descend to Pheriche for a good night\'s rest.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>8 - 9 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Pheriche<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 12\" place=\"Pheriche - Pangboche - Tengboche - Namche Bazaar (3,440m / 11,280ft)\"]\r\n\r\nToday, we trek down through the hillside blanketed by rhododendron and juniper trees. If it is spring, pink and red rhododendron flowers ablaze our surroundings. Depending on our hunger and condition, we either have our lunch in Pangboche or wait until we reach Phunki Tenga for lunch. After crossing the prayer flag festooned bridge over the Dudh Koshi River trail then follows the Dudh Koshi gorge descending rapidly through the pine forests. The path eventually reaches Sansa which is the major trail junction in the region. We stop at Kyangjuma (3570 m/11,710 ft) for a relaxed lunch. We unknowingly appreciate the gorgeous Ama Dablam, Thamserku and Nuptse with every bite. Following lunch, the trail to Namche Bazaar clings to the steep wooded slope beyond Kyangjuma, winding through several bends. We keep a lookout for wild life such as mountain goats, snow leopards, colorful pheasants, etc., while passing through the forest by the trail. After passing a Chorten, we reach the army camp at Namche Bazaar. At this point, we would like to take a long last look (and picture!) back to Lhotse, the tip of Everest and Tengboche. On reaching our lodge, we take a nice hot shower and have very relaxed sleep in our room in Namche Bazaar.\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time: </strong>5 - 6 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Namche Bazaar<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 13\" place=\"Namche Bazaar - Lukla (2,800m / 9,186ft)\"]\r\n\r\nThe trail descends steeply downward so we need to walk slowly and under control as our shaky legs continuously battle the rocky terrain. After crossing the suspension bridges over the fast flowing Dudh Koshi and its tributaries the trail becomes more level and natural. By today we start to get warmed up by the light breeze. Any remaining sore throats and colds will be gone by today as we pass through this charming mountain air. Although we are travelling the same route down, we feel completely different views. We snap a mixture of open plains, rhododendron and pine forests, and in the distance snow covered peaks. We walk through the Sherpa villages\' noticing impressive faith in Buddhism and culture of prayer stones and prayers flag while we walk through the villages. Upon arrival in Lukla, we stretch those sore legs and recall the experiences of the last couple of weeks. We experience the culmination of a fantastic trek on a happy note with everyone back safe and sound with smile on faces!\r\n\r\n<strong>Trekking Time:</strong> 6 - 8 hrs\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Lukla<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 14\" place=\"Lukla - Kathmandu\"]\r\n\r\nToday, we fly back to Kathmandu after our long mountain journey. The early morning flight drops us in Kathmandu. You can rest and relax throughout the day at hotel. If you get interested to take some gifts home from Nepal for family, friends and relatives, you can visit to some nearby shops or venture out in Thamel for typical Nepalese goods. This short excursion either can be assisted by Nepalaya Explorer guides or you can do it yourselves too. If you want to explore any other areas in Kathmandu, Nepalaya Explorer manages time for this today as well! At the evening will be at a fantastic celebration dinner together for successfully completing your trek to Everest Base Camp hosted by Nepalaya Explorer!\r\n\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Kathmandu<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast, Lunch, Dinner[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 15\" place=\"Lukla - Kathmandu\"]\r\n\r\nThe journey within the mountains of Nepal comes to an end today! There is nothing to do but just share emails with Nepalaya Explorer and we will organize your photos. If we have more time we can do some shopping or sightseeing. At least approximately 3 hours before your scheduled flight, a representative from Nepalaya Explorer drives you to the airport. On your way to home you will have plenty of time to plan your next adventure trip in the wonderful country of Nepal and in Asia with us.\r\n\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Kathmandu<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title=\"Day 15 - 18: Safari Option\" place=\"Chitwan National Park\"]\r\n\r\nStaying at the luxurious Temple Tiger Camp is a great way to finish off your trip. Set in the heart of the Royal Chitwan National Park you have some fantastic opportunities to see the prolific bird life, not to mention occasional sightings of the Royal Bengal Tiger, one horn rhinos and an amazing array of other wildlife. Naturalists are on hand with their seemingly endless supply of knowledge to answer your queries regarding all the species of animal in the park.\r\n\r\nWe recommend a short flight from Kathmandu to Bharatpur Meghauly airport (approx.-20 min.) or choose the road option for a 6-hr overland journey to Chitwan. private transportation in option as well approxi-6 hours.The lodge is made entirely of local materials and blends in beautifully with the environment. There is a range of activities to enjoy from elephant safaris to jungle walks, to just relaxing in the serene surroundings of the Lodge. Meals are all-inclusive and are a wonderful combination of Western and Nepali dishes. Accommodation is in spacious safari tents with twin beds and separate hot and cold showers. Since you do have to book in advance so please kindly inquiry or send us an email! We transfer you to Meghauly Airport (about 2 ½ hours away) where you will meet with your return flight to Kathmandu.\r\n\r\n<strong>Overnight: </strong>Temple Tiger Camp<strong>\r\nMeals Included:</strong> Breakfast[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Includes:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>State-of-the-art, international name-brand ISO-certified canyoning euipment, including wetsuit, specialized harness with PVC slider seat, PFD, helmet, splash top, ropes, carabiners, and figure eights.</li>\r\n 	<li>Licensed professional English-speaking local guides, highly trained and certified to national and international standards in canyoning techniques, advanced rope work, Swift Water Rescue 3, Nepal Red Cross CPR, and wilderness first aid</li>\r\n 	<li>Lunch and beverages</li>\r\n 	<li>Round trip transportation</li>\r\n 	<li>Adventure industry standard first aid kit</li>\r\n 	<li>Camping equipment</li>\r\n 	<li>Sleeping bag &amp; mat (upon request)</li>\r\n 	<li>3 meals daily</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Price Does Not Include:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\r\n 	<li>Unrelated transportation, visas, travel documents, etc.</li>\r\n 	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\r\n 	<li>Alcohol and junk food</li>\r\n 	<li>Bottled mineral water</li>\r\n 	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\r\n 	<li>Personal travel and health insurance</li>\r\n 	<li>Kayaks - can be rented upon request. Please inquire.</li>\r\n 	<li>Photos - Professional trip photos may be available at a small additional charge. Please inquire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title=\"Packing Aid:\"]\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Shorts</li>\r\n 	<li>Swim Suit</li>\r\n 	<li>Chacos or similar sport sandals that secure your heal</li>\r\n 	<li>Track pants (comfortable, loose-fitting, preferably synthetic)</li>\r\n 	<li>Fleece or other thermal top</li>\r\n 	<li>Jacket (waterproof shell)</li>\r\n 	<li>Socks</li>\r\n 	<li>Hiking boots</li>\r\n 	<li>Warm hat (in cooler seasons)</li>\r\n 	<li>Towel</li>\r\n 	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\r\n 	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\r\n 	<li>Sunglasses</li>\r\n 	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\r\n 	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\r\n 	<li>Waterproof sunscreen and lip balm (minimum SPF15)</li>\r\n 	<li>Any medications you may be taking</li>\r\n 	<li>Sleeping bag (if you don\'t have your own, we can provide you with a complementary bag)</li>\r\n 	<li>Personal first aid kit</li>\r\n 	<li>Water bottle</li>\r\n 	<li>Waterproof camera or GOPRO</li>\r\n 	<li>A little cash for treats and tips</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Everest Base Camp Trek', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '3441-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-03-22 07:38:47', '2017-03-22 07:38:47', '', 3441, 'http://dac.technocreates.net/nepalayaexplorer/2017/03/22/3441-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
